06187nam a22008295i 9780857451095DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574510957 a10.1515/97808574510952doi  a(DE-B1597)636016  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBL980.C39bD58 2011 7aHIS0400002bisacsh04a200.943/090322200aDiversity and Dissent :bNegotiating Religious Difference in Central Europe, 1500-1800 /ced. by Howard Louthan, Gary B. Cohen, Franz A. J. Szabo. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAustrian and Habsburg Studies ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Figures -- tNotes on Contributors -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Between Conflict and Concord: Th e Challenge of Religious Diversity in Central Europe -- t1. Constructing and Crossing Confessional Boundaries: The High Nobility and the Reformation of Bohemia -- t2. Religious Toleration in Sixteenth-Century Poland: Political Realities and Social Constraints -- t3. Customs of Confession: Managing Religious Diversity in Late Sixteenth- and Early Seventeenth-Century Westphalia -- t4. Cuius regio, eius religio: Th e Ambivalent Meanings of State Building in Protestant Germany, 1555–1655 -- t5. The Entropy of Coercion in the Holy Roman Empire: Jews, Heretics, Witches -- t6. Conflict and Concord in Early Modern Poland: Catholics and Orthodox at the Union of Brest -- t7. Confessionalization and the Jews: Impacts and Parallels in the City of Strasbourg -- t8. Mary “Triumphant over Demons and Also Heretics”: Religious Symbols and Confessional Uniformity in Catholic Germany -- t9. Heresy and Literacy in the Eighteenth-Century Habsburg Monarchy -- t10. Union, Reunion, or Toleration? Reconciliatory Attempts among Eighteenth-Century Protestants -- t11. Confessional Uniformity, Toleration, Freedom of Religion: An Issue for Enlightened Absolutism in the Eighteenth Century -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly modern Central Europe was the continent’s most decentralized region politically and its most diverse ethnically and culturally. With the onset of the Reformation, it also became Europe’s most religiously divided territory and potentially its most explosive in terms of confessional conflict and war. Focusing on the Holy Roman Empire and the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, this volume examines the tremendous challenge of managing confessional diversity in Central Europe between 1500 and 1800. Addressing issues of tolerance, intolerance, and ecumenism, each chapter explores a facet of the complex dynamic between the state and the region’s Catholic, Protestant, Orthodox, Utraquist, and Jewish communities. The development of religious toleration—one of the most debated questions of the early modern period—is examined here afresh, with careful consideration of the factors and conditions that led to both confessional concord and religious violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aReligious tolerancezEurope, CentralxHistoryvCongresses. 0aReligious tolerancezEurope, CentralxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh1 aBrady, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Gary B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDmitriev, Mikhail V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedeburg, Robert von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeal, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul